            ; we live at No. 15, Sherrard-street, Golden-square - my daughter 
               <persName id="t18310217-159-person1586">
                  Hannah 
                  Amelia
               <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1586" type="surname" value="Amelia"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1586" type="given" value="Hannah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1586" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             is five years old. On the 17th of January she had been at school the whole of the day, and ought to have returned at a quarter-past four o'clock, but she did not come till a quarter-past five, when she came without her bonnet, her bag, her book, and two or three other things - she was in a very fatigued state, and had been crying.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-159-person1587">
                  ANN 
                  HOLE
               <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1587" type="surname" value="HOLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1587" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1587" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I keep the school to which this child comes - I tied on her bonnet at four o'clock, on the 17th of January, and sent her home with her bag and her book; my house is not a quarter of a mile from the prosecutor's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-159-person1588">
                  ANN 
                  LOMAX
               <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1588" type="surname" value="LOMAX"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1588" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1588" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner came to my shop, No. 78, Monmouth-street, which is about fifty yards from the prosecutor's, on the 17th of January; she brought an old bonnet in her hand for sale; I asked what she wanted for it - she said 6d.; I said I could only sell it for that, and I offered her 4d. - I asked if it was her own; she said Yes, that her sister lived in a gentleman's family, and she should have many of these little things; this is the bonnet.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-159-person1589">
                  JOHN 
                  JAMES GANNELL
               <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1589" type="surname" value="JAMES GANNELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1589" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-159-person1589" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-constable. I saw the prisoner on my beat on the 17th of January; I watched her for some time - she went into a marine-store shop, and offered a small jug for sale; the woman would not buy it, as she said she had offered a bonnet for sale - the prisoner said she had sold the bonnet for 4d.; I went and inquired about it, then ran after the prisoner, and took her; she threw the jug away, and broke it - I said I wanted her for a bonnet; she denied it, but I took her to the station, and there she was recognized.</p>
